In [4]:
df = pd.read_csv('top50.csv', encoding = "ISO-8859-1")

Data source: https://www.kaggle.com/leonardopena/top50spotify2019

The top 50 most listened songs in the world by spotify. This dataset has several variables about the songs.

The data includes: 50 songs and 13 variables

Varaibale definition:

  1. Danceability: Describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity.

  1. Valence: Describes the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry).

  2. Energy: Represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude scores low on the scale.

  3. Beats per minute (BPM): the speed or pace of a given piece, and derives directly from the average beat duration.

  4. Loudness: The overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB). Loudness values are averaged across the entire track and are useful for comparing relative loudness of tracks.

  5. Speechiness: This detects the presence of spoken words in a track. The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g. talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value.

  6. Liveness: Detects the presence of an audience in the recording. Higher liveness values represent an increased probability that the track was performed live.

  7. Acousticness: A confidence measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic.

Bivariate Exploration

  • Beats Per Minute has a positive relationship with Speechness with the correlation of 0.56.
  • Energy has a strong relationship with Loudness and Valence but it has a negative relationship with Acousticness.
  • Danceability doesnt really have any strong relationships with other attributes.This means any songs in top 50 have an ability to make people dance regardless of other attributes.
  • Loudness has a ngative relationship with Speechness but strong positive relationship with Energy.
  • Liveness doesnt really have any extremely strong relationships with other attributes. However, it does have a negative relationship with Beats Per Minutes but positive relationship with Loudness and Ranking of the Songs.
  • Valence has a positive relationship with Energy but negative relationship with Popularity.
  • Length doesnt have any strong relationship with other attributes when all of absolute value of the correlations are less than 0.25.
  • Position (Unamed column) has a slightly positive relationship with Valence and Liveness but a negative one with Speechiness, Beats Per Minute and Popularity.
